[A group of paper-machine tenders in Holyoke,
                                            Massachusetts formed Eagle Lodge as a social club. May
                                            19, 1893, the American Federation of Labor issued a
                                            charter for the United Brotherhood of Paper Makers. Only
                                            paper machine tenders and beater engineers were
                                            included. In 1897, the organization asked AFL to widen
                                            their group to everyone in the papermaking trade.
                                            However, the paper machine tenders kept the new groups
                                            in separate lodges and did not allow them to vote. The
                                            name was changed in 1902 to the International
                                            Brotherhood of Paper Makers. At this time the federal
                                            labor unions for mechanics, firemen, pulp workers and
                                            laborers petitioned AFL for their own charter but it was
                                            denied. In 1903 these groups were transferred without
                                            their consent to the International Brotherhoood of Paper
                                            Makers. There was a period of unrest and in 1906 the
                                            pulp and paper mill workers established a separate
                                            group, the International Brotherhood of Pulp, Sulphite,
                                            and Paper Mill Workers. This group was not recognized by
                                            the AFL until 1909.] Information taken from Gross, James
                                            A., (1964). The Making and Shaping of Unionism in the
                                            Pulp and Paper Industry, Labor History, vol. 5, issue
                                            2

[Henricus de Segusio began his Lectura super
                                            Decretales in 1262, almost ten years after his more
                                            famous Summa super titulis Decretalium was finished.
                                            Cardinal Henricus entitled the work the Commentum super
                                            Decretalibus in his last will and testament, but the
                                            work is commonly known as the Lectura. The work was
                                            completed in two versions, the first completed circa
                                            1265, which exists in one manuscript in Oxford, New
                                            College MS 207. The second, longer version was finished
                                            near his death.]
